05241nam a22007815i 9780813570167DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2015    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135701677 a10.36019/97808135701672doi  a(DE-B1597)526486  a(OCoLC)895162844  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aCooper, Tova, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.14aThe Autobiography of Citizenship :bAssimilation and Resistance in U.S. Education /cTova Cooper. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b11 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Literatures Initiative00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. On Autobiography, Boy Scouts, and Citizenship: Revisiting Charles Eastman's Deep Woods -- t2. The Scenes of Seeing: Frances Benjamin Johnston and Visualizations of the "Indian" in Black, White, and Native Educational Contexts -- t3. Curricular Cosmopolitans: W. E. B. Du Bois and Jane Addams -- t4. Educating the Ostjuden: Abraham Cahan and Gestures of Resistance -- t5. Emma Goldman, the Modern School, and the Politics of Reproduction -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the turn of the twentieth century, the United States was faced with a new and radically mixed population, one that included freed African Americans, former reservation Indians, and a burgeoning immigrant population.  In The Autobiography of Citizenship, Tova Cooper looks at how educators tried to impose unity on this divergent population, and how the new citizens in turn often resisted these efforts, reshaping mainstream U.S. culture and embracing their own view of what it means to be an American.  The Autobiography of Citizenship traces how citizenship education programs began popping up all over the country, influenced by the progressive approach to hands-on learning popularized by John Dewey and his followers. Cooper offers an insightful account of these programs, enlivened with compelling readings of archival materials such as photos of students in the process of learning; autobiographical writing by both teachers and new citizens; and memoirs, photos, poems, and novels by authors such as W.E.B. Du Bois, Jane Addams, Charles Reznikoff, and Emma Goldman. Indeed, Cooper provides the first comparative, inside look at these citizenship programs, revealing that they varied wildly: at one end, assimilationist boarding schools required American Indian children to transform their dress, language, and beliefs, while at the other end the libertarian Modern School encouraged immigrant children to frolic naked in the countryside and learn about the world by walking, hiking, and following their whims.  Here then is an engaging portrait of what it was like to be, and become, a U.S. citizen one hundred years ago, showing that what it means to be "American" is never static.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aAmericanizationxHistoryy20th century. 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aEducationxDemographic aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxEducationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMinoritiesxEducationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813570167423Coveruhttp